## Bug Report

<!-- Thanks for your bug report! Don't worry if you can't fill out all the sections. -->

### What version of TiKV are you using?
<!-- You can run `tikv-server --version` -->
5.0.0-rc

### What operating system and CPU are you using?
<!-- If you're using Linux, you can run `cat /proc/cpuinfo` -->
Not related to the problem 

### Steps to reproduce
<!-- If possible, provide a recipe for reproducing the error. A complete runnable program is good. -->
Not related to the problem 

### What did happened?
The current statistical logic is as follows:
```rust
fn handle_tasks<W: WriteBatch<EK>>(
    &mut self,
    apply_ctx: &mut ApplyContext<EK, W>,
    msgs: &mut Vec<Msg<EK>>,
) {
    let mut channel_timer = None;
    ...
    loop {
        match drainer.next() {
            Some(Msg::Apply { start, apply }) => {
                if channel_timer.is_none() {
                    channel_timer = Some(start);
                }
                self.handle_apply(apply_ctx, apply);
                ...
            }
            ...
        }
    }
    if let Some(timer) = channel_timer {
        let elapsed = duration_to_sec(timer.elapsed());
        APPLY_TASK_WAIT_TIME_HISTOGRAM.observe(elapsed);
    }
}
```
I donâ€™t quite understand the purpose of such statistics.

### What did you expect?
Shouldn't the correct statistical logic be like this:
```rust
fn handle_tasks<W: WriteBatch<EK>>(
    &mut self,
    apply_ctx: &mut ApplyContext<EK, W>,
    msgs: &mut Vec<Msg<EK>>,
) {
    ...
    loop {
        match drainer.next() {
            Some(Msg::Apply { start, apply }) => {
                APPLY_TASK_WAIT_TIME_HISTOGRAM.observe(start.elapsed_secs());
                self.handle_apply(apply_ctx, apply);
                ...
            }
            ...
        }
    }
}
```
If I misunderstood something, please let me know.
Thanks.
